		<div class="comment-body"><p>Electrical resistance = heat. Your oven elements heat up and glow because of the potential across them and their resistance to current flow. I suspect you could build something similar, sized for 12V and the correct power output. </p>
<p>I&#8217;m no electrical engineer, but some trial, error, thick gloves, and lexan could get you there pretty quickly <img src="http://www.thesurvivalpodcast.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" class="wp-smiley" />  For example, I once used a 9V battery and a paper clip to start a fire. Just required some leather gloves to protect my fingers&#8230; a few seconds later, it was as if I had used a Bic.  </p>
<p>You could build a resistive circuit and waterproof it so you could submerge it in the water.  But there might be a commercial solution that is sufficiently cheap that it isn&#8217;t worth the time, effort, and safety hazard to  chase a DIY solution. Missouri Wind &amp; Solar pops up in Google with some 12V heating elements for $50. Here is a link to their 100W element &#8211; <a href="http://www.mwands.com/index.php?main_page=product_info&#038;cPath=40&#038;products_id=430" rel="nofollow">http://www.mwands.com/index.php?main_page=product_info&#038;cPath=40&#038;products_id=430</a></p>
</div>

